WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.690 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:13.450 --> 00:00:14.940
&gt;&gt; Michael Socolow: Let
me begin by welcoming you

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:17.470
and this is a different panel
because, as you've seen,

00:00:17.470 --> 00:00:19.260
most of the conference
has really been focused

00:00:19.260 --> 00:00:20.560
on public media.

00:00:20.560 --> 00:00:23.140
And Sam Berlowski, in the
transcription one, made a joke,

00:00:23.140 --> 00:00:26.450
he said about two people
remember who Frank Stanton was

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:29.660
and the CBS archive has
come up in a couple of times

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:30.960
and a couple of ways in there.

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:33.530
And it is the 50th anniversary
of Public Broadcasting,

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:35.400
but this is a place
that we're here to talk

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:37.870
about what commercial
broadcasting means in terms

00:00:37.870 --> 00:00:41.230
of radio preservation in
that way and how it works.

00:00:41.230 --> 00:00:44.200
Okay, so the panel is Dr.
Noah Arceneaux is an associate

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:45.500
professor in the school of --

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:47.550
when I say your name
acknowledge, please --

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:50.120
is an associate professor
in the school of Journalism

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:52.250
and Media Studies at San
Diego State University.

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:55.840
His PhD from the University
of Georgia examines the role

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:57.540
of department stores
during the early years

00:00:57.540 --> 00:01:00.150
of American broadcasting and
his subsequent research --

00:01:00.150 --> 00:01:02.290
and, by the way, if you haven't
read his article on technology

00:01:02.290 --> 00:01:05.970
and culture on Wanamaker Stores
in the early nineteen teens,

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:09.490
it's terrific -- his subsequent
research has explored the social

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:12.840
construction of new media
technologies as well

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:14.580
as emerging forms
of mobile media.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.940
He's the coeditor of,
in Academic Studies,

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:19.550
of Cell Phones, the
Cell Phone Reader,

00:01:19.550 --> 00:01:23.740
and in 2012 he added an update
titled The Mobile Media reader,

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:26.780
Dr. Arceneaux spent the
spring of 2014 in India

00:01:26.780 --> 00:01:29.950
on a Fullbright-Nehru
research grant and prior

00:01:29.950 --> 00:01:32.300
to joining academia, Dr.
Arceneaux produced websites

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:35.930
for ABC, CBS, and the
FOX television networks.

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:39.510
Although she's a respondent,
she's actually going to go next

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:41.570
after Dr. Arceneaux
is Heather Birks.

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:43.790
Heather Birks has been
the executive director

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:47.270
of the Broadcast Education
Association since 2006.

00:01:47.270 --> 00:01:50.220
Before coming to BEA she worked
for the NAB for four years

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:54.100
and the NABEF for six where
she helped to build, manage,

00:01:54.100 --> 00:01:57.400
and produce the Service to
America Awards and launched

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.470
and ran the Broadcast
Leadership Training Program.

00:02:00.470 --> 00:02:02.230
Birks oversees BEA's
partnerships

00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:05.850
and coordinates BEA's annual
convention: The Festival

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:09.900
of Media Arts, and the regional
BEA On Location conferences.

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:12.900
She works closely with the Radio
Advertising Borough and NAB

00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:15.920
to run the Radio Show
Student Scholars program,

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:18.510
which assists students
interested in careers in radio,

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:20.830
and in June 2017
Birks was named one

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:24.640
of Radio Inc's 2017 Most
Influential Women in Radio.

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:30.730
Professor Kathy Fuller-Seeley is
the William P. Hobby Centennial

00:02:30.730 --> 00:02:32.170
Professor of Communication

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:34.860
in the Radio Television Film
department of Moody College

00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:37.340
of Communication at the
University of Texas.

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:41.330
Dr. Fuller-Seeley's research
focuses on American film, radio,

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:44.310
and television history and
audience reception studies.

00:02:44.310 --> 00:02:47.070
I could tell you about all of
her wonderful Hollywood books,

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:50.070
but I'm just too excited
because her new book, Jack Benny

00:02:50.070 --> 00:02:55.770
and the Golden Age of Radio
Comedy, came out just last week,

00:02:55.770 --> 00:02:59.640
published by University of
California Press, very exciting,

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.740
and Dr. Fuller-Seeley has
received a National Endowment

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.920
for the Humanities fellowship
for university teachers

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.710
to support the project.

00:03:06.710 --> 00:03:08.590
Dr. Fuller-Seeley has
published numerous articles

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:10.990
and book chapters on early TV
and Hollywood film audiences

00:03:10.990 --> 00:03:12.360
and performers and she's served

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:15.800
as a historical consultant
for PBS.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:18.680
Okay, Alex, Dr. Alex
Kupfer -- Kupfer?

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:19.980
Sorry.

00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:21.280
&gt;&gt; Dr. Alex Kupfer: Kupfer.

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:22.580
&gt;&gt; -- Kupfer is currently
visiting assistant professor

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:23.880
in the film department
at Vassar College.

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:25.700
He received his PhD from the
Department of Cinema Studies

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:29.000
at New York University's Tisch
School of the Arts and his MA

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.780
in Cinema and Media
Studies from UCLA.

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:33.430
His current book project
chronicles the relationship

00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:36.090
among collegiate
football, the American film

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:41.250
and radio industries, and
higher education before 1960.

00:03:41.250 --> 00:03:45.730
Okay, then Mary Ann Watson,
Dr. Mary -- I'm sorry --

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:48.620
Dr. Mary Ann Watson is the
author of The Expanding Vista:

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:50.570
American Television
in The Kennedy Years

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:52.430
and Defining Visions: Television

00:03:52.430 --> 00:03:55.140
and The American Experience
in the 20th Century.

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:57.090
Dr. Watson has contributed
book chapters

00:03:57.090 --> 00:03:58.720
to many works including
the Columbia History

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:01.350
of American Television
and she is the coeditor,

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:03.690
and for today this is
really the important one,

00:04:03.690 --> 00:04:06.510
she's the coeditor of Norman
Corwin's One World Flight:

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:09.550
The Lost Journal of
Radio's Greatest Writer,

00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:11.490
who she interviewed, right?

00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:14.380
Before he died, which is
a great connection there.

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:17.350
Dr. Watson has received
research awards

00:04:17.350 --> 00:04:19.370
from the Rockefeller Foundation
and National Endowment

00:04:19.370 --> 00:04:22.000
for the Humanities and
she's served as a consultant

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.010
to several documentaries
including Color Adjustment:

00:04:25.010 --> 00:04:27.880
Blacks in Prime Time, Making
Sense of the Sixties, JFK,

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:30.930
and JFK Breaking the
News, all of which aired

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.570
on American Public Television.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:35.970
Okay, next is Cynthia Meyers

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:42.360
and Dr. Cynthia B. Meyers
is an associate professor

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:44.910
of communication at Mt. St.
Vincent College in New York

00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:47.960
and the author of A Word from
Our Sponsor: Admen, Advertising,

00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:49.260
and The Golden Age of Radio

00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:52.210
which received the Broadcast
Historian Prize from the Library

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:55.010
of American Broadcasting
Foundation in 2016.

00:04:55.010 --> 00:04:57.920
She's written numerous articles
and book chapters on the history

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:00.290
and culture of the American
Advertising industry

00:05:00.290 --> 00:05:02.730
and its often overlooked
role in the production

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:05.800
of commercial broadcast
programming.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:08.490
And, then, Ross Melnick.

00:05:08.490 --> 00:05:11.270
Dr. Ross Melnick
specializes in media,

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.800
industry history
analysis, and is the author

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.320
of American Showman: Samuel
"Roxy" Rothafel and the Birth

00:05:17.320 --> 00:05:20.600
of the Entertainment
Industry, 1908-1935,

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.640
published by Columbia
University Press.

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:25.960
His research has been
published in numerous journals,

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:28.460
including Cinema Journal,
Film History, Moving Image,

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.180
Historical Journal of
Film and Television --

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:32.560
Film, Radio, and Television.

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:33.860
How could I leave that out?

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:38.470
He was named an Academy film
scholar in 2017 by the Academy

00:05:38.470 --> 00:05:39.850
of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:42.290
and awarded a National Endowment
for the Humanities fellowship

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:45.620
in 2015-2016, and was
a postdoctoral fellow

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:49.600
at Fox Center for Humanistic
Inquiry at Emory University.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:52.490
Prior to completing his
doctorate, he served as curator

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:54.530
of the collection at the
Museum of the Moving Image.

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:57.040
He's been an archivist
and, very interestingly,

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.430
he's worked in film marketing
in the commercial industry

00:05:59.430 --> 00:06:01.960
for Miramax, MGM,
and DreamWorks.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:05.100
Okay, our commercial
respondents.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:08.810
First is, not to put you in --

00:06:08.810 --> 00:06:10.570
&gt;&gt; Ross Melnick: I've
never been described

00:06:10.570 --> 00:06:12.450
as a commercial respondent.

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:13.750
&gt;&gt; Michael Socolow:
Michael Freedman.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:15.800
In a distinguished career
spanning more than 35 years,

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.920
Michael Freedman has
served as general manager

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:21.060
of CBS Radio Network
News, managing editor

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:23.620
for the Broadcast Division of
United Press International,

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:25.500
a senior vice-president
of the University

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:29.580
of Maryland University College,
Leadership press secretary

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:32.920
for the majority whip of the
US House of Representatives,

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:34.540
vice-president of communications

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:36.790
for George Washington
University, GW Professor

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:38.720
of Journalism, and
executive director

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:41.400
of the University's
Global Media and Institute,

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:44.310
where he's produced the Public
Broadcasting series The Kalb

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:48.090
Report and the weekly network
radio programs, This Just In

00:06:48.090 --> 00:06:51.150
and GW Presents American Jazz.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:53.100
Over the course of his
career, Freedman's collaborated

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:56.300
on programming such icons as
Walter Cronkite, Marvin Kalb,

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:59.020
Tony Bennett, Ernie
Harwell, Robert Trout,

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:02.300
Richard C. Hottelet, Dan
Rather, and Charles Osgood.

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:05.520
Freedman is co-author of The
Broadcast Voice Handbook,

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.700
and a contributing author to
Broadcasting Through Crisis,

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:11.730
Responsible Journalism, and
The Encyclopedia of Journalism.

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:14.080
He's a member of The National
Press Club Board of Governors

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:16.750
and The Museum Educator
Advisory team, and has served

00:07:16.750 --> 00:07:18.780
on the advisory boards of
the Duke Ellington School

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:22.990
of the Arts, The RTDNA, and
The Radio History Society.

00:07:22.990 --> 00:07:25.330
Sam Litzinger.

00:07:25.330 --> 00:07:26.630
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: That's me.

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:27.930
&gt;&gt; Michael Socolow: Sam is --

00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:33.200
I hear Sam every weekend on
620 AM, WZON in Bangor, Maine.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:34.610
Stephen King's station, so.

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:37.130
This is quite a --
everybody in Bangor knows Sam.

00:07:37.130 --> 00:07:40.290
Sam Litzinger joined CBS New
in September 1998 serving

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.670
as both anchor and
reporter for CBS Radio News.

00:07:42.670 --> 00:07:46.100
Before CBS, Litzinger helped
create The World Radio Public

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:48.730
Radio Network based in
Kentucky and he's worked

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:50.480
for mutual NBC Radio, CNN,

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:52.450
and The Associated
Press Radio Network,

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:53.750
as well as several commercial

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:56.660
and public radio operations
throughout the United States.

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:59.450
Litzinger has reported from
England, France, Spain, Poland,

00:07:59.450 --> 00:08:02.520
Germany, Israel, two miles
inside of Mammoth Cave,

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:05.280
and from a ship in the middle
of a North Atlantic storm.

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:08.920
Among his notable interviews are
the Dalai Lama, Scotty Moore,

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:12.030
Lemmy from the heavy metal
band Motorhead, Richard Nixon,

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:15.270
that's an interesting
[laughter], Tony Bennett,

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:18.290
Maya Angelou, and the
Florida man who specializes

00:08:18.290 --> 00:08:20.070
in capturing alligators
that wander

00:08:20.070 --> 00:08:21.590
into people's swimming pools.

00:08:21.590 --> 00:08:23.380
Litzinger was born in
Titusville, Pennsylvania,

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:25.650
where he began his
broadcasting career at 16

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.960
and he has a master's degree
in comparative philosophy

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:30.080
from the University of Hawaii.

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:32.110
And, then, Shawn VanCour.

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:35.840
Shawn is an assistant professor
of media archival studies

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:37.490
at UCLA's department
of information studies.

00:08:37.490 --> 00:08:40.240
His scholarship focuses on
the history and preservation

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:41.900
of early radio and
television programming

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:43.200
in the United States.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:46.140
His book, Making Radio: Early
Radio Production and the Rise

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.520
of Modern Sound Culture,

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.740
forthcoming from
Oxford University Press,

00:08:49.740 --> 00:08:52.390
traces the development of
dominant production practices

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:55.210
and performance styles for
early US radio and their impact

00:08:55.210 --> 00:08:57.800
on adjacent fields of
film and music recording.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:59.450
Okay. So, to end
the introduction,

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:03.350
I asked the members of the panel
just to do very basic things.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:04.890
The first, I asked
the scholars to speak

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:06.190
about their interactions

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:09.260
with commercial broadcasting
community as scholars,

00:09:09.260 --> 00:09:10.870
researchers, and educators,

00:09:10.870 --> 00:09:12.980
and I asked our commercial
broadcasting representatives

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:15.690
to reflect a bit on how
historical audio is used

00:09:15.690 --> 00:09:16.990
and preserved in the industry.

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:19.220
And, the goal of this panel
is actually discussion.

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:20.760
We also want to hear from you.

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.060
We want to think
about how scholars

00:09:22.060 --> 00:09:24.220
and researchers can work
with commercial broadcasters

00:09:24.220 --> 00:09:26.670
for educational and
research purposes.

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:28.310
So, Noah, take it away.

00:09:28.310 --> 00:09:29.610
&gt;&gt; Noah Arceneaux:
Good afternoon.

00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:32.080
I felt a little strange
when I realized

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:33.860
that I was slotted
on this panel.

00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.500
My dissertation completed,
now, 10 years ago,

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:39.410
it was about the origins
of commercial broadcasting,

00:09:39.410 --> 00:09:42.040
which is why Josh probably
threw me in this slot,

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:44.240
but after I completed
my dissertation,

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:48.280
I started to do research on even
earlier era; the pre-radio era

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.020
of wireless telegraphy.

00:09:50.020 --> 00:09:52.260
As Michael mentioned,
I wrote something.

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:56.520
Wanamaker's Department Store
had wireless telegraph in 1911,

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:59.300
the New York Herald was
transmitting news via Morse code

00:09:59.300 --> 00:10:00.600
even earlier than that.

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:06.420
We don't have recordings of
these things and the fact --

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:08.680
it's just never really crossed
my mind would there even

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:09.980
be recordings?

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:11.680
Who would record Morse
code transmission?

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:14.570
I only know of one such
recording from that era.

00:10:14.570 --> 00:10:16.670
What I wanted to share with
you, and I'm just going

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:19.830
to take full advantage of this
opportunity because I'm on stage

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:21.460
and I have a projector
so I'm going

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:24.550
to take full advantage
of this opportunity.

00:10:24.550 --> 00:10:26.850
Because of my research
into wireless telegraphy,

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:28.670
I spent the summer in Oxford;

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:32.090
the Marconi archives are
at the library there.

00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:33.480
The Bodleian Library.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:35.340
I was told on my first
day it's not 'Bowedlean',

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:36.710
and you sound like
a dumb American.

00:10:36.710 --> 00:10:38.010
The 'Bodleian'.

00:10:38.010 --> 00:10:41.720
So, I spent two months there
digging through the archives,

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:44.450
photographing as much as I
could and I found this document.

00:10:44.450 --> 00:10:46.520
This is what I wanted
to share with you.

00:10:46.520 --> 00:10:48.520
And I was aware, of course,

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:51.230
of the Radio Preservation
Task Force

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:55.060
and I thought this is a
really weird artifact.

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:57.140
This is a radio recording?

00:10:57.140 --> 00:11:01.320
Maybe? It's a composition
book from 1897.

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:06.720
Okay? Marconi had one of his
employees go out on the ocean

00:11:06.720 --> 00:11:09.010
in a harbor and was
sending signals back

00:11:09.010 --> 00:11:13.420
to a station located
on the Isle of Wight.

00:11:13.420 --> 00:11:15.780
And they recorded the
transmissions on little strips

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.400
of paper and I found many
of these strips of paper.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:22.590
But for some reason they pasted
these into a child's notebook,

00:11:22.590 --> 00:11:26.350
which has an essay
about Celtic Britain.

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:28.240
So, of course, I find
myself reading the essay

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:30.250
and admiring this
child's penmanship,

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:31.870
which is much better than mine.

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:36.810
Yeah. 1897, that's a 7, not a 4.

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:40.840
So, I was, okay, Marconi
-- he's doing wireless,

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:42.760
which will eventually
become radio.

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:44.650
He wants to make money.

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:46.780
I'll just scroll through.

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:48.460
He wants to make money.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:50.630
That's a commercial service.

00:11:50.630 --> 00:11:55.010
Is this recording
of commercial radio?

00:11:55.010 --> 00:11:56.310
Maybe. I don't know.

00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:58.050
Depends on how you
define radio, right?

00:11:58.050 --> 00:11:59.860
Now what is the academic
significance of this?

00:11:59.860 --> 00:12:01.160
I have no idea.

00:12:01.160 --> 00:12:02.510
What's the theoretical
implication of this?

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:03.810
I don't know.

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:05.110
I just thought this was
really weird and cool

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:06.410
and I wanted to share it.

00:12:06.410 --> 00:12:09.620
Right? So, that's
what I'm doing.

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:14.920
I thought maybe I could turn
these strips of paper back

00:12:14.920 --> 00:12:17.950
into Morse code and make my
students build a radio receiver.

00:12:17.950 --> 00:12:20.090
Would there be some
academic value of that?

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:21.390
I'm not sure.

00:12:21.390 --> 00:12:24.020
But, in terms of
my dissertation,

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:28.300
which was about 1920s radio,
my argument, in a nutshell,

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:31.370
was that there was
advertising on American radio

00:12:31.370 --> 00:12:32.720
from the very beginning.

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.350
And this is not commonly
acknowledged

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:38.980
because we don't have
recordings from 1920 and 1921.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:44.120
A station owned by AT&amp;T, WEAF,
airs the first radio commercial.

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.770
This is in all the
textbooks that we use.

00:12:46.770 --> 00:12:49.410
This is memorialized
as a significant first.

00:12:49.410 --> 00:12:52.090
I was looking at
department stores

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:53.560
that had their own
radio stations

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:54.860
and I'm just convinced --

00:12:54.860 --> 00:12:57.460
common sense tells me
the department stores

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.600
were advertising.

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:02.570
In the program listings that
were listed in the newspapers,

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:06.020
they had programs about shoes,
programs about women's coats.

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:08.690
Surely they were doing
ads for those products.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:11.350
And some of the listings in
the newspapers would even say,

00:13:11.350 --> 00:13:14.140
"Music brought to you
by Victor Records".

00:13:14.140 --> 00:13:16.160
Well, if they're putting
it in newspaper listing,

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:19.560
surely they must have been
saying it on the air as well,

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:22.630
but because we don't
have a recording of it,

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:25.150
WEAF and AT&amp;T get the credit.

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:28.220
The one book on the
commercialization of radio

00:13:28.220 --> 00:13:30.360
by Susan Smulyan, I
don't think she's here.

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:32.090
Is that correct?

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:35.450
Really privileges the networks
because those are the records

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:36.990
that we have and I believe

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:40.730
that there was really just some
explicit commercialism going on.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:44.350
And the reason I think this
era is important is this is

00:13:44.350 --> 00:13:46.290
when everything was really
formed and established,

00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:48.680
the network system, the
commercial broadcasting system,

00:13:48.680 --> 00:13:53.250
the rules that we still are
following to some degree today.

00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:55.280
So I think it would be good

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:57.900
if we could understand the
origins a little better.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:02.160
But obviously -- there are
some recordings from 1920s.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:03.480
I won't say there are none.

00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:05.710
I talked with Chuck
Howell and Mike Henry

00:14:05.710 --> 00:14:07.460
when I was doing my
dissertation research.

00:14:07.460 --> 00:14:10.250
From being at this conference,

00:14:10.250 --> 00:14:12.410
I've learned there are
maybe some more recordings

00:14:12.410 --> 00:14:13.810
from that era that
have been uncovered

00:14:13.810 --> 00:14:17.040
but we don't have anything like
a thorough, complete coverage.

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:20.900
But obviously commercial radio
is a dominant form of radio.

00:14:20.900 --> 00:14:22.930
I don't mean to malign
public radio

00:14:22.930 --> 00:14:25.060
but that's what many
people listen to.

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:26.360
And there'd just be

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:28.650
such tremendous value
if we had more of it.

00:14:28.650 --> 00:14:30.640
And I'm not talking
about program logs

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:32.410
or what music was
played on what station.

00:14:32.410 --> 00:14:33.900
We can uncover the music,

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:35.650
but it's the advertising
that we want.

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:37.400
It's the local announcers.

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:40.590
It's that regional feel.

00:14:40.590 --> 00:14:44.560
And this lack of recordings --

00:14:44.560 --> 00:14:47.620
it's not that the problem
has gone away as we all know.

00:14:47.620 --> 00:14:50.760
In 2011, there was a
massive power outage

00:14:50.760 --> 00:14:52.060
in southern California.

00:14:52.060 --> 00:14:53.360
It was really remarkable.

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:55.260
Basically, Los Angeles
down to the border.

00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:58.180
It was like all of southern
California lost power.

00:14:58.180 --> 00:15:01.050
San Diego people went berserk.

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:04.310
Like it was the zombie
apocalypse coming.

00:15:04.310 --> 00:15:07.750
Your ATM wouldn't work because
there was no electricity,

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:09.120
so the ATMs wouldn't work.

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:10.420
Cell phones were dying.

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:13.210
There was only one radio station
in San Diego that managed

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:15.360
to stay on the air
for the duration.

00:15:15.360 --> 00:15:16.910
The power was back
on by midnight.

00:15:16.910 --> 00:15:18.210
It only lasted a half a day.

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:19.880
But only one radio
station, KPBS,

00:15:19.880 --> 00:15:22.600
our local PBS station
went off the air.

00:15:22.600 --> 00:15:24.890
One local news station,
an AM station,

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:26.430
managed to stay on the air.

00:15:26.430 --> 00:15:29.580
And I have a representative
from Nielson come to my classes

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:32.130
and talk and he shared
with me the ratings data

00:15:32.130 --> 00:15:33.670
from that particular day.

00:15:33.670 --> 00:15:35.880
As you can imagine, there
was this unbelievable spike

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:37.340
at four o'clock in
the afternoon,

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:40.150
every single radio
tuned to that station

00:15:40.150 --> 00:15:42.490
because it was the only
thing that was going on.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:44.620
And when I called
them, they don't --

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:46.310
I mean they have a
record of what happened

00:15:46.310 --> 00:15:48.380
but there's no actual recording.

00:15:48.380 --> 00:15:51.930
I don't think it even
crossed anyone's mind, hey,

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:53.640
this is an historic moment.

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:57.190
So, maybe that gives people
some things to think about

00:15:57.190 --> 00:15:59.280
and respond to, but I wanted
to share this with you.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:01.580
Thank you for indulging me.

