00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:32.470
But if I can tell one very
quick story about the importance

00:20:32.470 --> 00:20:36.510
of Jack Benny's show to
commercial radio, at large,

00:20:36.510 --> 00:20:39.430
in the business and
consumer economy,

00:20:39.430 --> 00:20:42.460
is quickly the story of Jell-O.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:47.960
I can't resist telling the story
of Jell-O in one minute or less.

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:52.120
Jell-O in the spring and fall
of 1934 was a dying product.

00:20:52.120 --> 00:20:53.420
It was 40 years old.

00:20:53.420 --> 00:21:00.230
It's competition, even A&amp;P
Jell-O, cost half the price

00:21:00.230 --> 00:21:01.640
and tasted twice as good.

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:05.370
So, General Foods was
about to sink the product

00:21:05.370 --> 00:21:06.780
and put it out of business.

00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:10.240
But, indeed an advertising
agency Young and Rubicam

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:13.520
and I learned so much
about the importance

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:16.560
of advertising agencies as
creative and business forces.

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:18.210
For instance, Cynthia Meyers.

00:21:18.210 --> 00:21:23.100
Advertising agency Young and
Rubicam came to General Foods

00:21:23.100 --> 00:21:24.740
in the Jell-O division
and they said,

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:26.380
"You've got one last shot."

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:29.790
They said, "You have your
chemist fix the taste,

00:21:29.790 --> 00:21:33.030
you have your marketers
cut your price in half.

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:36.650
We'll pick up some talent and
we'll give it one last shot."

00:21:36.650 --> 00:21:38.380
Because back in the day,

00:21:38.380 --> 00:21:43.310
if a radio audience
enjoyed the programming,

00:21:43.310 --> 00:21:46.960
they were being trained to go
out and purchase the product.

00:21:46.960 --> 00:21:48.690
So they said, "One shot."

00:21:48.690 --> 00:21:50.290
Jack Benny was not
their first choice.

00:21:50.290 --> 00:21:51.590
He was about their
fourth choice.

00:21:51.590 --> 00:21:55.330
He had been fired by his
previous three sponsors

00:21:55.330 --> 00:21:58.660
because he was determined
to be his own show runner.

00:21:58.660 --> 00:22:02.400
He wouldn't let them tell
why kind of comedy to do,

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:03.840
what kind of programming to do.

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:06.270
So, he's kind of a retread.

00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:08.500
But Young and Rubicam said,
"Let's give it a shot.

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:11.440
He was really funny with
the advertisements."

00:22:11.440 --> 00:22:14.690
So they bring Benny and
Mary Livingstone on board.

00:22:14.690 --> 00:22:18.330
They start the Jell-O
program in October 1934.

00:22:18.330 --> 00:22:21.550
And in the first two months,
the comedy was really great

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:23.500
but no Jell-O is selling.

00:22:23.500 --> 00:22:25.360
Even though the price
has been cut.

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:27.900
And, General Foods is going,
"Well, everybody now has

00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:29.350
to work at half price.

00:22:29.350 --> 00:22:30.760
We're going to cut
the salaries."

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:33.880
And Jack Benny and Mary
Livingstone say, "Okay.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:36.920
We'll work without salary
for the next 10 weeks.

00:22:36.920 --> 00:22:40.900
Give us that long to try and
get sales of a product boosted

00:22:40.900 --> 00:22:42.430
and then we'll call it quits."

00:22:42.430 --> 00:22:45.810
So, for 10 weeks they worked
without salary so that the rest

00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:49.360
of the cast could
still earn a living.

00:22:49.360 --> 00:22:51.260
And they sell the
heck out of Jell-O.

00:22:51.260 --> 00:22:56.090
Don Wilson wears a striped tie
in the lemon, lime, cherry,

00:22:56.090 --> 00:22:58.930
and orange striped variety.

00:22:58.930 --> 00:23:00.670
They do skits.

00:23:00.670 --> 00:23:03.350
Talk about Romeo
and Jell-O-ette.

00:23:03.350 --> 00:23:05.270
They are on the Good
Ship Jell-O.

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:09.100
They're just Jell-O-ing every
six ways you could think of it.

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:14.730
And about eight weeks later,
sales start to skyrocket.

00:23:14.730 --> 00:23:18.250
Pretty soon, they are
selling more Jell-O

00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:21.170
than can actually be
made at the factory.

00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:23.630
They're in a small town
in upstate New York.

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:26.850
They end up having to buy
other products and rebrand them

00:23:26.850 --> 00:23:30.660
as Jell-O just to have enough
for Jack Benny to sell.

00:23:30.660 --> 00:23:37.340
By Christmastime, early January,
General Foods was so happy

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:39.230
at this complete
business turn-around,

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:42.900
here's the selling power of
radio, of commercial radio,

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:46.690
they had a party at Jack
and Mary's apartment.

00:23:46.690 --> 00:23:50.540
They provided one of
those big lottery checks

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:53.850
for all of their back salary.

00:23:53.850 --> 00:23:56.140
They said you've
saved our product.

00:23:56.140 --> 00:24:00.980
Hooray. Just wait until
we get Bill Cosby.

00:24:00.980 --> 00:24:02.280
No. I kid you.

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:05.050
They weren't that prescient.

00:24:05.050 --> 00:24:10.550
So, literally, a radio comedy
program turned the fortunes

00:24:10.550 --> 00:24:14.410
of a consumer product and the
only joke Mary Livingstone had

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:17.540
to say about it was that the
company had provided a great big

00:24:17.540 --> 00:24:21.100
tray of shimmering red
Jell-O and she told the maid,

00:24:21.100 --> 00:24:23.400
"Get that crap outta here."

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:26.510
Which she was a little
sorry got overheard.

00:24:26.510 --> 00:24:30.790
But, working on Benny
was a wonderful project

00:24:30.790 --> 00:24:32.090
because I thought of him --

00:24:32.090 --> 00:24:35.070
I wanted to tell the story
of the radio show instead

00:24:35.070 --> 00:24:37.330
of the story of his
private life.

00:24:37.330 --> 00:24:39.670
And I found he was a
tremendous show runner,

00:24:39.670 --> 00:24:43.720
advertising creator, and
executive and intermedia star,

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:47.470
and an incredible
maestro and director

00:24:47.470 --> 00:24:49.750
of the timing of
his [inaudible].

00:24:49.750 --> 00:24:51.190
Please. Enjoy my book.

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:53.510
It's half price on
Kindle [inaudible].

