00:24:58.040 --> 00:24:59.340
&gt;&gt; Alex Kupfer: Sure.

00:24:59.340 --> 00:25:01.670
I want to talk just for a
few minutes about one example

00:25:01.670 --> 00:25:04.870
of where some of my research
in radio has taken me as a way

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:07.980
to sort of offer some of
these questions about access

00:25:07.980 --> 00:25:10.330
and preservation of
materials and then how

00:25:10.330 --> 00:25:12.800
that shapes scholarship
potentially.

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:14.970
And, the example that I want
to discuss actually came

00:25:14.970 --> 00:25:17.100
out of the first
RPTF conference.

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:18.810
And it was some research
that I had started to do

00:25:18.810 --> 00:25:21.430
on a show called The Land
Grant College Radio Hour,

00:25:21.430 --> 00:25:24.590
which aired in the 1930s
on NBC Blue Affiliates.

00:25:24.590 --> 00:25:28.400
So, just very briefly, this
was a monthly show that came

00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:30.760
out of the National Farm
and Home Hour series.

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:33.640
And during The Land Grant
the first few years,

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:37.070
it would feature three
talks on domestic topics,

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:38.370
or agricultural topics,

00:25:38.370 --> 00:25:40.450
delivered by speakers
supplied either

00:25:40.450 --> 00:25:43.560
by a rotating university
extension program

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:45.490
or the US Department
of Agriculture.

00:25:45.490 --> 00:25:49.200
By the 1930s, interest had
really waned in the show

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:50.500
and it was rehauled as kind

00:25:50.500 --> 00:25:52.660
of this traveling
road show program.

00:25:52.660 --> 00:25:54.550
Once a month, it
would be broadcast

00:25:54.550 --> 00:25:57.250
from a different land
grant college radio station

00:25:57.250 --> 00:25:58.850
from throughout the country.

00:25:58.850 --> 00:26:01.850
So, this was a really
interesting production process

00:26:01.850 --> 00:26:04.560
because even at schools
which had their own stations,

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:06.900
it was fairly collaborative
between NBC

00:26:06.900 --> 00:26:08.810
and faculty and students.

00:26:08.810 --> 00:26:11.750
So, NBC for instance, offered
technical support, equipment,

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:14.270
and some of the music you used
in the show as well as sort

00:26:14.270 --> 00:26:17.690
of legal support over getting
the rights to this music,

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:19.990
while faculty and students
kind of did the rest,

00:26:19.990 --> 00:26:22.280
including perform
the entire show.

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:25.080
So, the lectures that
were initially part

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:28.110
of the show were replaced by
kind of more general promotion

00:26:28.110 --> 00:26:31.200
of each school's service to
the state and sort of histories

00:26:31.200 --> 00:26:32.940
about the state and
the university.

00:26:32.940 --> 00:26:35.690
So, there were things like
historical reenactments

00:26:35.690 --> 00:26:38.240
and interviews and various
musical performances

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:40.130
by different campus groups.

00:26:40.130 --> 00:26:43.700
Between 1936 and
1940, it was produced

00:26:43.700 --> 00:26:47.410
at 47 different land grant
colleges in 44 different states,

00:26:47.410 --> 00:26:49.790
ranging from Hawaii to Maine.

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:52.610
So, I think the Land Grant
College Radio Hour raises a lot

00:26:52.610 --> 00:26:54.270
of sort of interesting
issues related

00:26:54.270 --> 00:26:56.440
to access and preservation.

00:26:56.440 --> 00:26:58.550
So, because of this
decentralized collaborative

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:01.050
model between NBC and
the different schools,

00:27:01.050 --> 00:27:03.300
there is no single,
real, archival home

00:27:03.300 --> 00:27:05.960
for documents related
to the program.

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:07.260
So, in practical terms too,

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:10.250
this also means very few
[inaudible] episodes.

00:27:10.250 --> 00:27:14.700
I found four episodes going
literally episode by episode

00:27:14.700 --> 00:27:18.130
and contacting different
archives and universities.

00:27:18.130 --> 00:27:20.290
Records can be very
difficult to find.

00:27:20.290 --> 00:27:22.540
So, for instance, records
documenting the development

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:25.130
of the show were housed at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison

00:27:25.130 --> 00:27:27.590
in the Wisconsin
Historical Society.

00:27:27.590 --> 00:27:30.540
And actually to fly to
the University of Nevada

00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:31.870
to listen to their recordings.

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:34.500
They were one of the few
who had transcription discs.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:36.420
And luckily they were
nice enough to transfer it

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:38.430
to a record where I could
later play it for my students.

00:27:38.430 --> 00:27:41.140
And they had also the files
related to the production

00:27:41.140 --> 00:27:44.620
of the show as well as things
like letters from alumni

00:27:44.620 --> 00:27:46.820
from across the country
who are really interested

00:27:46.820 --> 00:27:49.580
in hearing their school
being discussed on the air.

00:27:49.580 --> 00:27:53.540
So, dealing with multiple
archives is not exceptional.

00:27:53.540 --> 00:27:55.380
I'm sure all the people
here could really talk

00:27:55.380 --> 00:27:57.580
about the dozens
potentially archives

00:27:57.580 --> 00:28:00.250
that they worked
on over the years.

00:28:00.250 --> 00:28:03.520
But I think it does pose a
challenge for how scholars

00:28:03.520 --> 00:28:06.210
and archivists can address
situations like this show

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:09.490
where to discuss it, you
realistically would have to go

00:28:09.490 --> 00:28:12.940
to numerous archives,
potentially up to four dozen,

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:14.370
to find where the
show was recorded.

00:28:14.370 --> 00:28:16.320
And this is because
it's an example

00:28:16.320 --> 00:28:19.000
where you have this commercial
material from the networks

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.440
which had been mixed into
institutional collections.

00:28:22.440 --> 00:28:25.170
So, it's not housed in
NBC records but in each

00:28:25.170 --> 00:28:26.810
of these different
university archives.

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:29.910
So, I'll just sort of stop here
just by posing this question.

00:28:29.910 --> 00:28:33.200
Again, how can we formulate
ways to find this material

00:28:33.200 --> 00:28:36.220
to make it accessible and then
ultimately to preserve it?

00:28:36.220 --> 00:28:38.020
Thank you.

00:28:38.020 --> 00:28:47.040
