00:32:00.480 --> 00:32:02.120
&gt;&gt; Cynthia Meyers:
Is this working?

00:32:02.120 --> 00:32:04.180
Hi, I'm Cynthia Meyers

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:06.540
and I wrote a book called
A Word From Our Sponsor.

00:32:06.540 --> 00:32:09.750
I just want to make
one or two points

00:32:09.750 --> 00:32:13.880
about doing historical
work in media industries.

00:32:13.880 --> 00:32:16.810
First of all, Heather and I were
talking over lunch about some

00:32:16.810 --> 00:32:19.840
of the challenges when
we're also dealing

00:32:19.840 --> 00:32:22.510
with commercial entities
and companies

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:24.740
that might have records
or recordings

00:32:24.740 --> 00:32:26.700
or archives or materials.

00:32:26.700 --> 00:32:30.860
Getting access to them is very
difficult, and for many, many,

00:32:30.860 --> 00:32:32.160
many reasons, and I know

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:34.450
that we've had conversations
here this week

00:32:34.450 --> 00:32:35.750
about some of those reasons.

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:37.050
But, one of the things
I was talking to Heather

00:32:37.050 --> 00:32:39.910
about was the fact that
history, for a lot of people

00:32:39.910 --> 00:32:41.230
in the media industry
is something

00:32:41.230 --> 00:32:42.820
to be embarrassed about.

00:32:42.820 --> 00:32:46.710
It's not something
necessarily to be proud of.

00:32:46.710 --> 00:32:49.400
Because those old shows
are kind of funny.

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:50.930
You know, they're sort of weird.

00:32:50.930 --> 00:32:53.080
And, they're old fashioned.

00:32:53.080 --> 00:32:58.890
And connecting the current
today, forward thinking company

00:32:58.890 --> 00:33:01.730
with these sort of
old-fashioned artifacts

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:04.380
or these old fashioned ideas
or these old-fashioned forms

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:07.130
of culture is not always
something that they want to do.

00:33:07.130 --> 00:33:10.000
And so some of the issues, and I
hope we can talk about it today,

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.750
about private entities,
how they save,

00:33:12.750 --> 00:33:14.540
or don't save, their materials.

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:17.740
I think we need to remember
those of us, the archivists

00:33:17.740 --> 00:33:20.350
and the scholars, that it's
not just a financial issue

00:33:20.350 --> 00:33:23.470
or storage issue, it's also
there's a cultural sort

00:33:23.470 --> 00:33:26.930
of attitude issue and as
educators, we really need

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:30.320
to reach out and try to
figure out how to make some

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:34.110
of those companies feel that
their history is valuable rather

00:33:34.110 --> 00:33:36.170
than something to be
embarrassed about.

00:33:36.170 --> 00:33:38.990
The other point I was going to
make was just that we all know

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:42.770
about the [inaudible] of
media and especially radio.

00:33:42.770 --> 00:33:44.770
We talked about how
there's very little of it

00:33:44.770 --> 00:33:46.290
that has actually
been preserved.

00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:48.830
Well, this is also
true of advertising.

00:33:48.830 --> 00:33:52.110
Print advertising in magazines
is pretty well preserved

00:33:52.110 --> 00:33:54.320
because there are lots and
lots and lots and lots and lots

00:33:54.320 --> 00:33:55.620
of copies of magazines.

00:33:55.620 --> 00:33:58.370
So, a lot of advertising
history really is based

00:33:58.370 --> 00:34:01.550
on magazine advertising because
you can actually access it,

00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:03.120
which is great.

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:05.780
So, when I try to write
about radio and the role

00:34:05.780 --> 00:34:08.730
of advertising agencies in
radio, naturally, there are not

00:34:08.730 --> 00:34:11.920
that many recordings
or that many records

00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:14.530
because it's ephemeral
and it's a media industry.

00:34:14.530 --> 00:34:17.710
But, what also happened with
some radio recordings is

00:34:17.710 --> 00:34:19.780
that the advertising elements

00:34:19.780 --> 00:34:23.370
in the recordings are
sometimes cut out.

00:34:23.370 --> 00:34:26.570
So, there are all sorts of
recordings circulating out there

00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:29.760
like in the OTR community in
which that Lipton Tea commercial

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:32.130
in the inner sanctum
just doesn't appear.

00:34:32.130 --> 00:34:35.470
As a scholar, of course, I
want that context and I want

00:34:35.470 --> 00:34:38.450
to be able to understand
how those things sounded

00:34:38.450 --> 00:34:39.970
in those media artifacts.

00:34:39.970 --> 00:34:41.660
So, I'm just going
to put it out there

00:34:41.660 --> 00:34:45.550
that not only are the radio
programs ephemeral and difficult

00:34:45.550 --> 00:34:49.000
to preserve and capture, but
then the role of the ad industry

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:50.300
and the importance

00:34:50.300 --> 00:34:53.080
of the advertising texts
themselves were not seen

00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:56.690
as important by some people who
are preserving these things.

00:34:56.690 --> 00:35:00.040
And as we're looking forward
as archivists and scholars,

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:01.340
what are the things today

00:35:01.340 --> 00:35:03.280
that we're not thinking
are important now

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:04.580
but may be important
in the future.

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:06.200
That is something that I
think we need to keep in mind.

