&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: It's
still an FCC requirement,

01:44:55.940 --> 01:44:57.240
correct, is that?

01:44:57.240 --> 01:44:59.270
It never was an FCC requirement?

01:44:59.270 --> 01:45:03.150
For those of you who don't
know, back in the old days,

01:45:03.150 --> 01:45:05.040
when I was starting in radio.

01:45:05.040 --> 01:45:06.770
You had this thing that
was called a logger reel.

01:45:06.770 --> 01:45:10.770
And it was a slow-moving,
gigantic reel.

01:45:10.770 --> 01:45:13.880
And it would slowly turn
around and, in theory,

01:45:13.880 --> 01:45:17.500
it recorded every single thing
that went out over the air

01:45:17.500 --> 01:45:19.820
on your radio station
for that day.

01:45:19.820 --> 01:45:21.990
Then at the end of the
day, the midnight guy had

01:45:21.990 --> 01:45:24.760
to change the logger reels,
or however long it was.

01:45:24.760 --> 01:45:27.600
Some of them would last
like three days or five days

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:28.900
or a week or something.

01:45:28.900 --> 01:45:31.140
But then somebody pulled
them off and, theoretically,

01:45:31.140 --> 01:45:32.680
they were stored some place.

01:45:32.680 --> 01:45:36.180
And that was required at every
radio station I worked at up

01:45:36.180 --> 01:45:39.840
until I joined the
networks in the early '80s.

01:45:39.840 --> 01:45:45.080
&gt;&gt; I can add something
that I was going on now.

01:45:45.080 --> 01:45:48.290
The major radio station
in Atlanta, Georgia,

01:45:48.290 --> 01:45:52.220
it's been on the air
since about 1924,

01:45:52.220 --> 01:45:54.020
I know some people
who work there.

01:45:54.020 --> 01:45:55.650
They still have a
logging service.

01:45:55.650 --> 01:45:59.860
It's not a tape anymore, it's a
digital wav recorder type thing.

01:45:59.860 --> 01:46:03.180
And they're dumped after two
weeks or a month automatically.

01:46:03.180 --> 01:46:07.270
And he told me, and he would
know, cause he's big in news

01:46:07.270 --> 01:46:10.380
at that station, that the only
way anything is saved past

01:46:10.380 --> 01:46:13.570
that is if he wants,
specifically, to save something

01:46:13.570 --> 01:46:15.190
for his personal collection.

01:46:15.190 --> 01:46:17.830
And that's the policy
from the legal department.

01:46:17.830 --> 01:46:19.150
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: So
maybe that's some answer

01:46:19.150 --> 01:46:21.670
to your question, it's
not getting saved.

01:46:21.670 --> 01:46:23.340
A lot of it is not
getting saved.

01:46:23.340 --> 01:46:26.400
&gt;&gt; We did have our Born
Digital panel this morning.

01:46:26.400 --> 01:46:30.030
Denver, you were on that,
did this come up at all

01:46:30.030 --> 01:46:33.310
for current commercial content
or was it more podcast focused?

01:46:33.310 --> 01:46:34.610
More podcast?

01:46:34.610 --> 01:46:35.910
Okay.

01:46:35.910 --> 01:46:37.210
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: Yeah,
if you can get something

01:46:37.210 --> 01:46:39.720
on the web it's likely to
live, but if you don't put it

01:46:39.720 --> 01:46:42.230
on the web then it's
likely not to live.

01:46:42.230 --> 01:46:43.530
It seems to me.

01:46:43.530 --> 01:46:46.990
I started at this little station
in Titusville, Pennsylvania,

01:46:46.990 --> 01:46:49.440
that used to save all
of its logger reels.

01:46:49.440 --> 01:46:52.160
You know, and it had, like,
hundreds of these logger reels

01:46:52.160 --> 01:46:55.570
and then the station got sold to
somebody and the truck pulled up

01:46:55.570 --> 01:46:58.020
and they dumped it all
out and it's all gone.

01:46:58.020 --> 01:47:00.930
So you know, if you don't
make a conscious effort

01:47:00.930 --> 01:47:04.470
to save this stuff, it's
unlikely to get saved.

01:47:04.470 --> 01:47:06.300
&gt;&gt; Alright, now I'm
Thomas Witherspoon.

01:47:06.300 --> 01:47:09.310
I'm actually here representing
a project we're working

01:47:09.310 --> 01:47:12.060
on called the Spectrum Archive,
The Radio Spectrum Archive.

01:47:12.060 --> 01:47:13.430
I don't know how
many of you were

01:47:13.430 --> 01:47:18.520
in the curation panel
yesterday or the forum,

01:47:18.520 --> 01:47:22.930
but basically we've
been enthusiasts, fans,

01:47:22.930 --> 01:47:25.620
have been making
spectrum recordings,

01:47:25.620 --> 01:47:29.410
which are not an audio recording
of an individual broadcast

01:47:29.410 --> 01:47:32.460
on an individual
frequency, but a recording

01:47:32.460 --> 01:47:36.900
of the entire AM broadcast
band, for example, all at once.

01:47:36.900 --> 01:47:38.920
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: How
the heck do you do that?!

01:47:38.920 --> 01:47:40.220
[ Inaudible ]

01:47:40.220 --> 01:47:41.520
Oh.

01:47:41.520 --> 01:47:42.820
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so you're -- yeah.

01:47:42.820 --> 01:47:45.440
You're --

01:47:45.440 --> 01:47:48.060
It's, yeah it's about
one and a half megahertz

01:47:48.060 --> 01:47:50.070
to get the entire
AM broadcast band.

01:47:50.070 --> 01:47:51.760
You can also do the
FM broadcast band,

01:47:51.760 --> 01:47:56.710
shortwave bands,
and -- it's, pardon?

01:47:56.710 --> 01:47:58.010
[ Inaudible ]

01:47:58.010 --> 01:48:00.630
Yeah, yeah, it's
actually not that wide.

01:48:00.630 --> 01:48:02.220
The archives, I mean,

01:48:02.220 --> 01:48:04.460
the spectrum recordings
are quite large,

01:48:04.460 --> 01:48:07.550
so they're not easy
to manipulate.

01:48:07.550 --> 01:48:12.270
But, you know, for the past
two presidential elections,

01:48:12.270 --> 01:48:16.130
for example, I recorded the AM
broadcast band as it was heard

01:48:16.130 --> 01:48:17.960
in Asheville, North Carolina.

01:48:17.960 --> 01:48:19.830
So during the day,
local stations.

01:48:19.830 --> 01:48:21.660
At nighttime you could
hear things from all

01:48:21.660 --> 01:48:23.990
across North America of course.

01:48:23.990 --> 01:48:26.250
So you can go back now

01:48:26.250 --> 01:48:31.070
with a software defined radio
application, take my file,

01:48:31.070 --> 01:48:33.490
and you can tune through it
as if it were live radio.

01:48:33.490 --> 01:48:35.770
It's all the radio
stations and the static

01:48:35.770 --> 01:48:38.980
in between, everything.

01:48:38.980 --> 01:48:45.680
And, so, that's one way around,
I guess, having a logger reel is

01:48:45.680 --> 01:48:51.010
that people can make recordings
of more than just station.

01:48:51.010 --> 01:48:53.240
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: And what
are you doing with this?

01:48:53.240 --> 01:48:56.370
&gt;&gt; Well, right now, I'm trying
to find a home for these files.

01:48:56.370 --> 01:49:00.550
At home, right now, talk about
an endangered collection.

01:49:00.550 --> 01:49:02.390
I have 50 terabytes

01:49:02.390 --> 01:49:07.880
of recordings dating
back, for me, to 2011.

01:49:07.880 --> 01:49:11.210
I've actually got recordings
that were made by other people

01:49:11.210 --> 01:49:13.880
that date back all
the way to 1986.

01:49:13.880 --> 01:49:17.760
In fact, one of the clips I
showed yesterday in the forum,

01:49:17.760 --> 01:49:23.200
back in 1986, a radio enthusiast
in Providence, Rhode Island --

01:49:23.200 --> 01:49:27.910
in fact, that's the recording
right there, he's bringing up --

01:49:27.910 --> 01:49:30.820
that is an SDR application.

01:49:30.820 --> 01:49:33.960
And this is, you
know, how it works.

01:49:33.960 --> 01:49:35.620
It doesn't look like a
radio it looks like peace

01:49:35.620 --> 01:49:38.950
of test equipment, but all
of those little peaks you see

01:49:38.950 --> 01:49:41.360
on the line and the
waterfall display above,

01:49:41.360 --> 01:49:43.940
that's what you call that;
those are all radio stations.

01:49:43.940 --> 01:49:48.120
And it was recorded
on a VCR, a Hi-Fi VCR.

01:49:48.120 --> 01:49:51.960
Someone tapped into the
intermediate frequency

01:49:51.960 --> 01:49:55.560
on the receiver and
recorded it to the VCR

01:49:55.560 --> 01:49:57.610
and then they actually
played back the VCR tape

01:49:57.610 --> 01:49:58.910
through the radio.

01:49:58.910 --> 01:50:01.060
Well, later, just a
couple of years ago,

01:50:01.060 --> 01:50:03.690
he actually digitized this
so that we could play it

01:50:03.690 --> 01:50:05.930
through an SDR application.

01:50:05.930 --> 01:50:09.250
This is what it looks like,
I guess, if it can roll --

01:50:09.250 --> 01:50:11.150
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger: And can
you find something specific

01:50:11.150 --> 01:50:12.450
on this if you were looking?

01:50:12.450 --> 01:50:14.760
&gt;&gt; Recording: -- there is no
way of knowing just how bad

01:50:14.760 --> 01:50:18.440
that Chernobyl nuclear
plant disaster really is.

01:50:18.440 --> 01:50:21.950
In the talk of the western world
there are still vast portions

01:50:21.950 --> 01:50:26.050
of the Soviet Union that have
no idea that anything is wrong.

01:50:26.050 --> 01:50:28.660
[Inaudible] with Stanford
University says the only people

01:50:28.660 --> 01:50:31.970
in the Soviet Union
who were told

01:50:31.970 --> 01:50:33.270
about Chernobyl are
in Moscow and Kiev.

01:50:33.270 --> 01:50:38.630
We've been monitoring these
broadcasts since Tuesday,

01:50:38.630 --> 01:50:42.830
there's been absolutely no
mention of anything connected

01:50:42.830 --> 01:50:44.130
to a nuclear accident.

