01:51:16.080 --> 01:51:17.380
&gt;&gt; Recording: -- live from
the Kennedy Space Center

01:51:17.380 --> 01:51:18.680
this evening.

01:51:18.680 --> 01:51:19.980
It's the first launch there

01:51:19.980 --> 01:51:21.390
since the Challenger
Space Shuttle explosion.

01:51:21.390 --> 01:51:23.610
One Challenger investigator
says examination

01:51:23.610 --> 01:51:25.420
of wreckage proves a
rocket joint failed.

01:51:25.420 --> 01:51:27.290
Again pointing to a problem --

01:51:27.290 --> 01:51:28.590
&gt;&gt; Sam Litzinger:
That's interesting.

01:51:28.590 --> 01:51:30.630
The problem, though,
would be, I mean,

01:51:30.630 --> 01:51:32.980
other than for scholarly
purposes, we couldn't use

01:51:32.980 --> 01:51:34.930
that audio because
it's too terrible.

01:51:34.930 --> 01:51:37.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah, exactly.

01:51:37.110 --> 01:51:40.690
It's mainly, you know, for me
I would kind of classify myself

01:51:40.690 --> 01:51:41.990
as a radio anthropologist.

01:51:41.990 --> 01:51:45.610
So for me, this is very
context rich stuff.

